english:
  title: A Guest's Question
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When I was in Hadong, a guest came to my humble home and asked me, "Who were Kija and Pikan?" I replied, "They were virtuous ministers of the Yin dynasty." The guest pressed further, "One became a slave, the other remonstrated and died—which was the more virtuous?" I answered, "Both attained benevolence." Then the guest asked, "If you were placed in service to the Yin house, which would you choose to become—Kija or Pikan?" I replied, "Should I face slavery, I would be a slave. Should I face death through remonstration, I would die."

    The guest was displeased and said, "You understand that Kija and Pikan were virtuous and benevolent—that is well enough. But if you yourself were in their position, you could not choose between the two, could not abandon one and embrace the other. Is your learning not merely words that pass through the ears, lacking true understanding gained through experience?"

    I responded, "Let me explain what I have long considered. When the Yin dynasty declined, both men remonstrated with King Zhou. In those moments of fearless speech at court, Kija did not cherish his life, nor did Pikan deliberately seek death. Both wished to correct Zhou's wickedness and restore him to righteousness. But since Zhou was angered by Kija's words, he grew even more hostile to Pikan's. Thus one was enslaved and one was killed—not because of the depth of their resolve, but because of the varying degrees of the king's anger. Were slavery and death their intention from the start? Now when you ask me which was more virtuous—slavery or remonstration unto death—you are bound by the outward forms of their deeds. But both men spoke from hearts genuinely devoted to their lord and anxious for their state. In living, they sought no profit; in dying, they pursued no fame. One gave his body in service to principle, the other achieved righteousness through death. Both may serve as models for all under heaven and for generations to come. This is why I cannot choose between them, cannot abandon one and take the other.

    Confucius said, 'In the Yin there were three such men. Their paths differed, yet all are called benevolent.' Thus the sage judges people by their hearts—how could he be concerned with the mere traces of their actions? Moreover, when sages and worthies encounter chaotic times, they accept death or life, poverty or dignity as circumstances allow, each simply fulfilling their own way. None of this can be imitated by ordinary folk like ourselves." The guest then thanked me and departed. Thus I have recorded these words.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Kija (箕子) and Pikan (比干) were ministers under King Zhou of the Yin (Shang) dynasty. Kija famously remonstrated with the tyrant and was eventually enslaved; Pikan also remonstrated and was executed. Both are celebrated in Confucian tradition as exemplars of loyalty.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The reference to ''three men'' alludes to Confucius''s remark about the three virtuous men of the Yin: Kija, Pikan, and Weizi, who withdrew from service rather than remonstrate.'
  - key: ''
    value: Hadong (河東) likely refers to a region in what is now North Korea or Manchuria, where this author served.
